defaultQ3.default              defaultWhat should be done to ensure methods of calculating biomass GHG balance represent an accurate picture? default&#xa0;default12.
default 
defaultThe Greenhouse Gas 
default(GHG) lifecycle methodology for solid biomass and biogas used by the RHI is as set out under the 2009 EU Renewable Energy Directive
default. This EU approach considers the direct emissions impact of the biomass feedstock, from cultivation, harvesting, processing 
defaultand transport. 
default&#xa0;
default13.
default 
default The methodology used for the RHI does not include possible indirect impacts, such as indirect land use change. However, we consider it essential the UK uses the EU approach to provide consistency, to support a single European market, and 
defaultto avoid unnecessary burdens, particularly on smaller biomass producers and users. Moreover, the expectation is that most solid biomass or biogas used for heat in the UK will be from lower value residues or process waste: and, that where it is a dedicated 
defaultperennial energy crop, most will be grown on low quality or degraded land unsuitable for food production. 
default&#xa0;
default14.
default 
defaultDECC is currently developing a bioenergy calculator - the BEaC (Biomass Emissions and Counterfactual) Model, which will be in a format similar to DE
defaultCC’s existing 2050 pathways calculator. This model considers all potential GHG emissions, including indirect impacts and carbon stock changes in forests which are not accounted for by the 2009 EU Renewable Energy Directive. Users can choose various scenari
defaultos for bioenergy and the calculator then models lifecycle GHG emissions resulting from those scenarios.
default&#xa0;
default This tool will inform the UK’s future negotiations on global accounting and future energy and decarbonisation targets internationally. It will also be 
defaultused to inform 
defaultlong-term 
defaultbioenergy policies 
default.default&#xa0;default default&#xa0;defaultQ4.default              defaultThere are sustainability guidelines for biomass, do these go far enough?default&#xa0;default15.
default 
defaultThe use of biomass for heat  was identified by the UK Bioenergy Strategy
default as a low risk priority pathway that the UK would want to encourage. The high conversion efficiencies of heat generation
default 
defaultmean biomass heat is an attractive, cost-effective technology that c
defaultan
default make a significant contribution to the UK meeting its 2020 renew
defaultables target. 
defaultThe longer term role of biomass for heating is less straightforward (given the competing other users for which a finite bio-energy resource is likely to be needed), but modelling implies it could have a significant role, especially where high
default temperature heat is required, as in industrial processes. 
default&#xa0;
default16.
default 
defaultWe want the UK to be at the forefront in the EU in ensuring biomass supplies are sustainable and are bringing in robust RHI sustainability standards.  These are set out in the Government Response to 
default‘Providing Certainty, improving performance’
default consultation
default published in February
default and include a GHG lifecycle emissions target to ensure genuine emissions savings and land criteria to prevent deforestation or environmental degradation.
default&#xa0;
default17.
default 
defaultThe GHG lifecycle emissions target will be a minimum 60% GHG lifecycle saving
defaults compared to the GHG emissions of the EU fossil heat average; this is significantly tougher than the 35% initial saving recommended by the European Commission in their 2010 report
default. To be eligible for support, RHI installations will be required to demonst
defaultrate meeting the GHG target from April 2014; and the land criteria from April 2015.
default&#xa0;
default 
default&#xa0;
default18.
default 
defaultThe Government intends to review the effectiveness of the UK’s approach as part of the UK Bioenergy Strategy Review in 2017. 
default&#xa0;defaultQ5.default              defaultWhat will the local environmental impadefaultct be from the use of heat generation in urban areas, for example CHP units?default&#xa0;default19.
default 
defaultStudies suggest that biomass boilers and CHP
default, both biomass and natural gas fired,
default in urban areas could, in the absence of mitigating measures, have an adverse impact on; air qual
defaultity (particulate matter (PM) and oxides of nitrogen (NO
defaultx))
default and noise. The RHI is introducing emissions limits and targeted tariff values for biomass CHP and other biomass boilers which seek to mitigate their impact on air quality.  Air quality impacts will
default be kept under review. 
default&#xa0;
default20.
default 
defaultThe air pollutant emissions of biomass boilers and CHP plant 
default(of all fuel types) 
defaultabove 20MW thermal input are controlled by Environmental Permitting requirements.  Smaller plants are governed by the Clean Air Act 1993 and the 
defaultplann
defaulting process.  Defra has assisted with the development of guidance for local authorities on addressing air pollution impacts of CHP and biomass boilers. By careful plant location and good acoustic design, the noise impact of CHP can be mitigated. 
default&#xa0;
defaultQ6.default              defaultWhatdefault are the relative merits of using gas to directly provide space heating compared to centralised electricity production plus domestic heat pumps?default&#xa0;default default&#xa0;
default21.
default 
defaultDifferent approaches to heating bring different benefits.  
defaultH
defaulteat demand shows more variability than electricity demand across the day and across the seasons. UK electricity demand 
defaultvaries between 20 and 55
defaultGW
default daily
default.  Heat demand across all sectors can vary between 150 and 400GW during the coldest winter days. 
default&#xa0;
default22.
default 
defaultThe ga
defaults network helps manage variability
default,
default with suppliers able to purchase gas quickly from a number of sources. The gas grid is able to handle short term spikes in demand due to the gas market’s liquidity. The electricity grid is less able to accommodate spikes 
defaultin demand without substantial spare generation capacity to meet peak winter demand.
default&#xa0;
default23.
default 
defaultThe high-level conclusions of the economic modelling commissioned for the 
defaultMeeting the challenge 
defaultdocument suggest there could still be a limited role for natural gas in 205
default0 to meet peaks in heat demand on the coldest days of the year. It suggests this could be more cost-effective than the alternative of full electrification. We are also seeing the development of hybrid heating systems that use gas and renewable energy sourc
defaultes, which could play a part in meeting peak heat demand.  Energy efficient measures, smart meters, smarter electricity grids and developments in electricity and thermal storage will also help
default, as will the development of low carbon heat networks with multip
defaultle heat sources
default. 
default&#xa0;
default24.
default 
defaultWhen considering the relative merits of gas heating against electric heat pumps, costs of both fuel and infrastructure both now and in the future have to be considered.  For gas, there is the issue of the cost of maintaining the gas netw
defaultork; for electricity, there are the issues of the cost of reinforcement of the local electricity distribution grids. 
defaultIn both cases, some built-in redundancy is likely to be needed to ensure peak demand can be met.  This is why energy storage and demand-sid
defaulte response is so important. 
default&#xa0;
defaultQ7.default              defaultWhy is community heating/CHP not more common in the UK? default&#xa0;
default25.
default 
defaultThe amount of heat supplied to buildings in the UK via heat networks is around 2% of domestic, public sector and commercial heat demand. This amounts to around 2000
default networks serving approximately 210,000 dwellings and 1700 commercial and public buildings across the UK.
default&#xa0;
default26.
default 
defaultMany of the schemes in operation today in the UK originate from the 1960s and 70s. For a number of reasons, including the waning popularity of high-r
defaultise housing developments, and the poor design, construction
default, maintenance
default and economic performance of some early schemes, heat networks fell out of favour. 
defaultEuropean countries where they remained popular have tended to have less well-developed natural gas gr
defaultids than the UK. 
default&#xa0;
defaultOver the past decade, as local authorities have looked for ways to cut carbon emissions and address fuel poverty, the case for heat networks has strengthened. 
defaultConsumer reaction to networked heat is not straightforward; it can range from 
defaultvery positive where bills come down and reliability goes up (in comparison, for example, with electric heaters in a flat), all the way through to negative where a flat rate is charged, which is deemed to high and bearing no relation to actual heat consumed
default. The majority of heat consumers, however, are far more familiar with boilers and remain ignorant of the district heating option.
default&#xa0;
default27.
default 
default Government and other analysis over the previous years, including new modelling presented as an Annex to our March heat docum
defaultent, and responses from a wide variety of stakeholders, have shown that modern, low carbon heat networks can have a crucial role to play in a sustainable heating future, especially where heat demand is highly concentrated and a range of types of heat suppl
defaulty might be available, ie in urban areas. Major cities across the UK are already pursuing this route, but they often encounter barriers to development.. 
default&#xa0;
default28.
default 
defaultTo help local authorities and local economic partnerships to overcome the financial, commercial and te
defaultchnical skills barriers to developing low carbon heat networks,  DECC is establishing a new Heat Networks Delivery Unit to help local authorities and local economic partnerships to overcome the financial, commercial and technical skills barriers to develop
defaulting low carbon heat networks.  
defaultThis will be up and running by October this year[
defaultfootnote
default – 
defaultonce cleared, attach link to announcement of HNDU investment director appointment].
default&#xa0;
default29.
default 
defaultOver and above networked heat projects, 
defaultThe Government is keen to
default 
defaultsee more local
default communities getting involved in reducing energy use, managing energy demand and collectively purchasing energy to get a better deal.   We will be publishing a Community Energy Strategy in the autumn, which will identify the potential of community energy p
defaultrojects in the UK to bring benefits to communities while helping to tackle climate change and maintain energy security. It will consider how to help community energy projects overcome the main barriers they face.
default&#xa0;
default30.
default 
defaultUK CHP capacity has grown year on year to 
default6.1 GW
default  in 2012 contributing 6.4% of electricity generated. Most of this capacity (89%) is industrial supplying industrial process heat. The rate of growth has been slow, due to CHP projects facing significantly higher hurdle rates than power-only generat
defaultion projects and difficulties for small CHP operators in securing a good price for the electricity they produce. DECC is working on a bespoke policy to support deployment of additional CHP capacity
default, provided this can be shown to be lower carbon that the el
defaultectricity it is displacing
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ8.default              defaultWhat are the lock-in, costs and GHG savings from the promotion of different forms of domestic heating solution?default&#xa0;default31.
default 
defaultThe Committee has helpfully set out that it would like information on: 
default&#xa0;
default32.
default 
defaultThe share of the market for combi boilers is now approaching two-thirds of all boilers in the UK. The issue of the need for hot water tanks in the future was highlighted in 
defaultMeeting the Challenge
default. 
default&#xa0;
default33.
default 
defaultIndustry reports
default suggest that of those hou
defaultseholders that do not currently own a hot water tank, the proportion saying that they would find it easy to find space, and those saying it would be difficult, are of the same order. Technology may help that proportion of people who find the space requirem
defaultent for a new heat store difficult to meet.  First, hybrid heat pumps that incorporate condensing boilers will allow for the supply of hot water, thus negating much of the need for a thermal store. Secondly, developments in thermal storage, currently being
default researched by DECC, may make kit smaller and more efficient.  Thirdly, heat networks can offer storage capacity at scale, an important consideration in terms of matching supply with demand which in turn has wider benefits.
default&#xa0;
default Heat networks also enable easy 
defaulttransition between fossil fuel and low/zero carbon sources of heat. It allows changing on
defaulte 
default large heat supply 
default(or switching between a small number of different centralised heat sources) 
defaultrather than changing many individual boilers.
default&#xa0;
default 
default&#xa0;
default34.
default 
defaultAs stated above, the 
defaultUK encourages the use of biomass heat in buildings and for industrial processes
default.  
defaultSo, it is important that investors are given sufficient certainty to bring forward large scale investments without being subject to the risk that changing environmental and s
defaultustainability criteria will create stranded assets. Therefore we have decided that for existing non-domestic biomass RHI installations the sustainability criteria will be “grandfathered” from the date the criteria are first introduced under the RHI.  For n
defaultew biomass heat installations, including domestic installations, grandfathering of the criteria will be applied at the point of accreditation. In the longer-term, biomass sustainability controls could be changed, so new installations accredited after these
default changes may have to meet different standards.  We believe this offers a sensible balance between providing the certainty needed to bring forward new biomass heat generation while still allowing us the flexibility to adjust the controls for new installatio
defaultns
default.
default&#xa0;
default35.
default 
defaultNew installations of biomass systems will also need to meet air quality standards in relation to PM and NO
defaultx
default. Domestic legacy installations, installed between 15
defaultth
default July 2009 and the launch of the scheme, will not need to meet this requirement. The air
default quality standards will also apply to all biomass systems which join the non-domestic RHI from September 24
defaultth
default 2013. 
