defaultQ9.default              defaultShould the government take any further specific actions in relation to cooling?default&#xa0;default36.
default 
defaultCooling in the UK is primarily geared towards 
defaultremoving excessive heat gain in non-domestic buildings such as offices, to maintain comfortable ambient temperatures. Whilst mechanical cooling in buildings is currently responsible for 4% of the total energy demand, cooling in homes is less significant; a
defaultccounting for 1% of household energy use
default. Commissioned reports into the possible effects of climate change suggest that the domestic uptake of air conditioning
default is likely to
default rise. 
default&#xa0;
default37.
default 
defaultMeeting the Challenge
default proposed a number of areas that we need to examine i
defaultn tackling cooling in non-domestic buildings, such as improving our understanding of the way non-domestic buildings work and the way they are used to in relation to heating, ventilation and air conditioning systems. This is a complex area as the non-domest
defaultic building stock is diverse and the buildings are used so differently. Currently cooling is 
defaultpredominantly carried out through
default electric air conditioning although there are other measures that can be used as part of a new build or retrofit development. Our 
defaultMarch document, for example, pointed to the increased role for renewable systems, such as reversible heat pumps in heating and cooling buildings. There may also be scope to combine summer-time cooling with solar photovoltaic electricity generation. 
default&#xa0;
defaultWe are
default work
defaulting
default with industry and  wider stakeholder groups on these issues to decide on the specific actions that 
defaultmay be needed
default. 
