defaultQ10.default              defaultWhy does the RHI not seem to promote heat pumps successfullydefault?default&#xa0;
default38.
default 
defaultThe non-domestic RHI currently only incorporates ground source
default heat pumps (GSHPs).
default&#xa0;
default There is an existing strong and growing market for reversible air to air heat pumps (AAHPs) therefore we do not propose introducing RHI support for this technology. Towards the end of 2012, consultations closed which discussed the pos
defaultsibility of introducing support for heating-only AAHPs and air to water heat pumps. We are currently reviewing the responses and other evidence and plan to publish our decision as to whether or not RHI support is appropriate in autumn 2013.
default&#xa0;
default39.
default 
defaultIn response to industry and market feedback, DECC has looked at the evidence on cost data and heat usage assumptions used to set the levels of tariffs when the non-domestic scheme was launched alongside the level of uptake so far under the scheme and evide
defaultnce from the renewable heat industry and market. As a result of this, we launched 
defaultthe Non-Domestic Scheme Early Tariff Review consultation
default in June which set ou
defaultt how the Government proposed to respond to 
defaultthe low up take of some technologies, including GSHPs, in the scheme so far, to ensure that renewable heat can make an effective contribution to our 2020 renewable energy targets, support the UK renewable heat in
defaultdustry and achieve decarbonisation of our heat supply by 2050. The consultation has now closed and we plan to announce the outcomes this autumn.
default&#xa0;
default40.
default 
defaultAnother factor affecting the deployment of GSHPs is the construction industry.
default&#xa0;
default GSHPs are most commonly instal
defaultled as part of new-build construction projects, as retro-fitting is often not an option in older properties due to a lack of space for a suitably sized ground-loop.
default&#xa0;
default As the number of new-build construction projects have declined over the past few years, so
default has the demand for GSHP installations.
default&#xa0;
default41.
default 
defaultThe domestic scheme, which will open for applications in spring 2014, will support ground and air source heat pumps.
default&#xa0;defaultQ11.default              defaultHow successful will the RHI be when rolled out to households?default&#xa0;default42.
default 
defaultWe are confident that the dom
defaultestic RHI will successfully incentivise the uptake of renewable heat technologies, and anticipate 3.9TWh of 
defaultdomestic 
defaultrenewable heat will be supported through RHI by 2020/21. We estimate that this equates to cumulatively 745,000 installations by 2020/21. We
default expect to see steady growth in installations over the next few years, preparing the ground for mass rollout of renewable heating to households in the 2020s and 2030s. 
default&#xa0;
default43.
default 
defaultThe final policy was designed through extensive engagement over the consultation period, including consumer experience to date and consumer behaviour research by Ipsos MORI.
default 
default&#xa0;
default44.
default 
defaultWe are undertaking a range of activities to encourage uptake ahead of the schem
defaulte’s launch next year.
default&#xa0;
default The DECC-led RHI Consumer Protection and Empowerment and RHI Industry Advisory Groups are developing consumer engagement and industry promotional tools. Finally, DECC and Ofgem are working to streamline the application process.  
